Dimensions Tables 13

Continuation from step 11 -

In the same SSIS package where you have created the Source and destination connection manager - do the following dimension tables


1. DFT- DimIncidentDetails

Using SSIS Toolbox, the following components will be drag in the Control Flow Dashboard:

Drag and drop the Data Flow - right click Rename it as DFT- DimIncidentDetails.

Double click the Data Flow Task –

·         Drag and drop the OLE DB Source – Double click and add the Source connection manager and Data access mode select SQL Command – Copy the below code and paste in the SQL command text box.  And select OK.

select  
 [Incident Number w/year], 
[Year of Incident], 
[Type  Location], 
[Month of Occurence], 
[Day of the Week], 
[Incident Address], 
[Apartment Number],
      case when [Time of Occurrence] >= 4 and [Time of Occurrence] < 11 then 'Morning'
	  when [Time of Occurrence] >= 11 and [Time of Occurrence] < 18 then 'Afternoon'
	  when [Time of Occurrence] >= 0 and [Time of Occurrence] < 4 then 'Late Night'
	  else 'Night' end [Time of Occurrence]
from DallasCrimeData_Staging..DallasCrimeStaging
  where [Year of Incident] is not null 
  group by
  [Incident Number w/year], 
[Year of Incident], 
[Type  Location], 
[Month of Occurence], 
[Day of the Week], 
[Incident Address], 
[Apartment Number],
[Time of Occurrence]
  order by 
      [Year of Incident]

·         Drag and drop the derived column - use the Derived column Code and add the as shown in the Gif – Use the code below fig for creating the columns


·         Drag and drop Lookup and configure as follows

1.     General tab – Specify how to handle rows with no matching entries – select Redirect rows to no match output.

2.     Connection tab – OLE DB Connection manger – Select the destination connection manager and Use a table or a view – select DimIncidentDetails from the dropdown.

3.     Columns tab – make connection Source todestination as shown in fig and select OK                                                    


·         Make a Copy of the Lookup and then connect the First lookup to the copied lookup – select the option shown below-


·         Double click the 2nd lookup to go the Column Tab – unselect the Incidentkey and Match the Column from the source’s column to that in destination’s columns as shown in fig.


·         Drag and drop the OLE DB Command and make connection from the 2nd lookup to it – make connection as shown below fig.

 

·         Double click the OLE DB command to configure it

1.     Connection Manager Tab – connect to the destination connection manager

2.     Component Properties Tab – in the SQL command – copy and paste the below code   and select OK   

Update 
  [dbo].[DimIncidentDetails] 
set 
  [IncidentNumber] = ?, 
  [YearofIncident] = ?, 
  [TypeLocation] = ?, 
  [MonthofOccurence] = ?, 
  [DayWeek] = ?, 
  [TimeOccurred] = ?, 
  [IncidentAddress] = ?, 
  [ApartmentNumber] = ?, 
  [RecordFlag] = 1, 
  [EffectiveDate] = getdate(), 
  [EndDate] = getdate()-1 
where 
  [IncidentKey] = ?

3.     Column Mapping Tab – select the input column as shown in below fig and select OK

 

·         Drag and drop the OLE DB Destination and make connection from the 1st lookup to it – make connection as shown below fig.

 

·         Double click on the OLE DB Destination to config it

1.     Connection manager Tab – OLE DB Connection manager – Select the Destination connection manager & Name of the Table or View – Select the DimIncidentDetails table

2.     Mapping Tab – Connect the Column as shown in fig and Select OK

 



2. DFT - DimLocation

Using SSIS Toolbox, the following components will be drag in the Control Flow Dashboard:

Drag and drop the Data Flow - right click Rename it as DFT - DimLocation.

Double click the Data Flow Task –

·         Drag and drop the OLE DB Source – Double click and add the Source connection manager and Data access mode select SQL Command – Copy the below code and paste in the SQL command text box.  And select 

SELECT 
  [Zip Code], 
  [City], 
  [State], 
  [GeoCo-Ordinates] 
FROM 
[DallasCrimeData_Staging]..[DallasCrimeStaging] 
where 
  [Zip Code] is not null 
  and Len ([Zip Code]) >= 5 
  and State = 'TX' 
group by 
  [Zip Code], 
  [City], 
  [State], 
  [GeoCo-Ordinates]

·         Drag and drop the derived column - use the Derived column Code and add the as shown in the Gif – Use the code below fig for creating the columns


·         Drag and drop Lookup and configure as follows

1.     General tab – Specify how to handle rows with no matching entries – select Redirect rows to no match output.

2.     Connection tab – OLE DB Connection manger – Select the destination connection manager and Use a table or a view – select DimLocation from the dropdown.

3.     Columns tab – make connection Source to destination as shown in fig and select OK                                                       


·         Make a Copy of the Lookup and then connect the First lookup to the copied lookup – select the option shown below-

·         Double click the 2nd lookup to go the Column Tab – unselect the Loccationkey and Match the Column from the source’s column to that in destination’s columns as shown in fig.

·         Drag and drop the OLE DB Command and make connection from the 2nd lookup to it – make connection as shown below fig.



·         Double click the OLE DB command to configure it

1.     Connection Manager Tab – connect to the destination connection manager

2.     Component Properties Tab – in the SQL command – copy and paste the below code   and select OK   

Update [DimLocation] 
set 
  [City] =?, 
  [State] = ?, 
  [ZipCode] = ?, 
  [GeoCo-Ordinates] = ?, 
  [RecordFlag] = 1, 
  [EffectiveDate] = getdate(), 
  [EndDate] = Getdate()-1 
where 
  [LocationKey] = ?

3.     Column Mapping Tab – select the input column as shown in below fig and select OK


·         Drag and drop the OLE DB Destination and make connection from the 1st lookup to it – make connection as shown below fig.



·         Double click on the OLE DB Destination to config it

1.     Connection manager Tab – OLE DB Connection manager – Select the Destination connection manager & Name of the Table or View – Select the DimLocation  table

2.     Mapping Tab – Connect the Column as shown in fig and Select OK




3. DFT- DimDistrictCouncil

Using SSIS Toolbox, the following components will be drag in the Control Flow Dashboard:

Drag and drop the Data Flow - right click Rename it as DFT- DimDistrictCouncil.

Double click the Data Flow Task –

·         Drag and drop the OLE DB Source – Double click and add the Source connection manager and Data access mode select SQL Command – Copy the below code and paste in the SQL command text box.  And select OK.

SELECT  distinct
[Division]
,[Council District]
,[Target Area Action Grids]
,[Community]
   FROM
[DallasCrimeData_Staging].[dbo].[DallasCrimeStaging]
where [Council District] is not null 
group by [Division]
,[Council District]
,[Target Area Action Grids]
,[Community]

·         Drag and drop the derived column - use the Derived column Code and add the as shown in the Gif – Use the code below fig for creating the columns

For District  column use the code below and copy it in the expression.

[Council District] == "1" ? "D1" : ([Council District] == "8" ? "D8" : ([Council District] == "9" ? "D9" : ([Council District] == "10" ? "D10" : ([Council District] == "11" ? "D11" : [Council District]))))



·         Drag and drop Lookup and configure as follows

1.     General tab – Specify how to handle rows with no matching entries – select Redirect rows to no match output.

2.     Connection tab – OLE DB Connection manger – Select the destination connection manager and Use a table or a view – select DimDistrictCouncil from the dropdown.

                   3. Columns tab – make connection Source to destination as shown in fig and select OK                                                       


·         Make a Copy of the Lookup and then connect the First lookup to the copied lookup – select the option shown below-


·         Double click the 2nd lookup to go the Column Tab – unselect the Districtkey and Match the Column from the source’s column to that in destination’s columns as shown in fig.


·         Drag and drop the OLE DB Command and make connection from the 2nd lookup to it – make connection as shown below fig.


·         Double click the OLE DB command to configure it

1.     Connection Manager Tab – connect to the destination connection manager

2.     Component Properties Tab – in the SQL command – copy and paste the below code   and select OK   

Update 
  [DimDistrictCouncil] 
set 
  [CouncilDistrict] = ?, 
  [Division] = ?, 
  [TargetAreaActionGrids] = ?, 
  [Community] = ?, 
  [RecordFlag] = 1, 
  [EffectiveDate] = getdate(), 
  [EndDate] = getdate()-1 
where 
  [DistrictKey] = ?

3.     Column Mapping Tab – select the input column as shown in below fig and select OK


·         Drag and drop the OLE DB Destination and make connection from the 1st lookup to it – make connection as shown below fig.


·         Double click on the OLE DB Destination to config it

1.     Connection manager Tab – OLE DB Connection manager – Select the Destination connection manager & Name of the Table or View – Select the DimDistrictCouncil table

2.     Mapping Tab – Connect the Column as shown in fig and Select OK


4. DFT - DimInvestigationDetails

Using SSIS Toolbox, the following components will be drag in the Control Flow Dashboard:

Drag and drop the Data Flow - right click Rename it as DFT - DimInvestigationDetails.

Double click the Data Flow Task –

·         Drag and drop the OLE DB Source – Double click and add the Source connection manager and Data access mode select SQL Command – Copy the below code and paste in the SQL command text box.  And select OK.

select
[Element Number Assigned],
  [Modus Operandi (MO)],
[Investigating Unit 2]
from
 [dbo].[DallasCrimeStaging] 
where
[Element Number Assigned] is not null 
Group by
[Element Number Assigned],
  [Investigating Unit 2],
  [Modus Operandi (MO)]

·         Drag and drop the derived column - use the Derived column Code and add the as shown in the Gif – Use the code below fig for creating the columns 


·         Drag and drop Lookup and configure as follows

1.     General tab – Specify how to handle rows with no matching entries – select Redirect rows to no match output.

2.     Connection tab – OLE DB Connection manger – Select the destination connection manager and Use a table or a view – select DimInvestigationDetails from the dropdown.

3.     Columns tab – make connection Source to destination as shown in fig and select OK                                                   


·         Make a Copy of the Lookup and then connect the First lookup to the copied lookup – select the option shown below-


·         Double click the 2nd lookup to go the Column Tab – unselect the Investigationkey and Match the Column from the source’s column to that in destination’s columns as shown in fig.


·         Drag and drop the OLE DB Command and make connection from the 2nd lookup to it – make connection as shown below fig.


·         Double click the OLE DB command to configure it

1.     Connection Manager Tab – connect to the destination connection manager

5. DFT - DimBusiness

Using SSIS Toolbox, the following components will be drag in the Control Flow Dashboard:

Drag and drop the Data Flow - right click Rename it as DFT - DimBusiness.

Double click the Data Flow Task –

·         Drag and drop the OLE DB Source – Double click and add the Source connection manager and Data access mode select SQL Command – Copy the below code and paste in the SQL command text box.  And select OK.

select [Victim Business Name]
      ,[Victim Business Address]
      ,[Victim Business Phone]
              from
DallasCrimeData_Staging..DallasCrimeStaging
              where [Victim Business Name] is not null 
              group by [Victim Business Name]
      ,[Victim Business Address]
      ,[Victim Business Phone]

·         Drag and drop the derived column - use the Derived column Code and add the as shown in the Gif – Use the code below fig for creating the columns 



·         Drag and drop Lookup and configure as follows

1.     General tab – Specify how to handle rows with no matching entries – select Redirect rows to no match output.

2.     Connection tab – OLE DB Connection manger – Select the destination connection manager and Use a table or a view – select DimBusiness from the dropdown.

3.     Columns tab – make connection Source to destination as shown in fig and select OK                                                   

·         Make a Copy of the Lookup and then connect the First lookup to the copied lookup – select the option shown below-   


·         Double click the 2nd lookup to go the Column Tab – unselect the Businesskey and Match the Column from the source’s column to that in destination’s columns as shown in fig.


·         Drag and drop the OLE DB Command and make connection from the 2nd lookup to it – make connection as shown below fig.


·         Double click the OLE DB command to configure it

1.     Connection Manager Tab – connect to the destination connection manager

2.     Component Properties Tab – in the SQL command – copy and paste the below code   and select OK   

Update
[dbo].[DimBusiness]
set
[BusinessName] =?
,[BusinessAddress] =?
,[BusinessPhone] =?
 ,[RecordFlag] =1
,[EffectiveDate] =getdate()
,[EndDate] = getdate()-1
where [BusinessKey] =? 

3.     Column Mapping Tab – select the input column as shown in below fig and select OK

·         Drag and drop the OLE DB Destination and make connection from the 1st lookup to it – make connection as shown below fig.


·         Double click on the OLE DB Destination to config it

1.     Connection manager Tab – OLE DB Connection manager – Select the Destination connection manager & Name of the Table or View – Select the DimBusiness table

2.     Mapping Tab – Connect the Column as shown in fig and Select OK
